{{osm box|w|279530312}}

According to the company biography, in the first year of {{ill|lt=Taika|Q1077930|qid=Q1077930|1=Taika (era)}} ({{ill|lt=645|Q31040|qid=Q31040|1=645}}), {{ill|lt=Emperor Saimei|Q235296|qid=Q235296|lt=Emperor Kogyoku|1=Empress Kōgyoku}} was a dream. It is said that he received a message saying, ``Since I am Tenjin, there will be a tomb for the god in the lower soil, and I will enshrine the spirits there.'' He ordered {{ill|lt=Fujiwara no Kamatari|Q433995|qid=Q433995|lt=Nakatomi Kamatari|1=Fujiwara no Kamatari}} to build a shrine at Kobata-no-sho. When Prince Oama headed from Otsunomiya to Yoshino ahead of the {{ill|lt=Jinshin War|Q2378252|qid=Q2378252|1=Jinshin War}}, he placed a willow branch at the head of the shrine and prayed for victory, saying, ``If I ascend to the throne, this willow will sprout.'' It is said that when Prince Oama ascended the throne, a willow branch sprouted, and the Emperor gave him the name ``Yanagi Daimyojin'' and donated the shrine's territory in praise of his miraculous powers.

It is said to have been enshrined at its current location from Yanagiyama during the Oho era (1161-1163) <ref>``Japan Historical Place Names Daikei Volume 26 Place Names of Kyoto Prefecture'' Heibonsha, 1981, p227</ref>.1908 (ref) “Uji City History 3: Early Modern History and Landscape”, 1975, p457 Table 43. In addition, the history of the shrine states, ``Additional note: In January 1907, Tanaka Shrine was enshrined and continued to this day.'' Since Tanaka Shrine in the former Kawara Village was enshrined in </ref>, the company's enshrined deities {{ill|lt=Amaterasu Omikami|Q455602|qid=Q455602|lt=Amaterasu Omikami|1=Amaterasu}} and {{ill|lt=Amatsu Hikone-no-Mikoto|UNKNOWN|lt=Amatsu Hikone-no-Mikoto}} are also enshrined there.

Within the precincts, there is Tomb No. 36 of {{ill|lt=Ujiryo|Q38277767|qid=Q38277767|1=Uji Mausolea}} called ``Foxzuka,'' which is said to be the tomb of {{ill|lt=Fujiwara Mototsune|Q1397196|qid=Q1397196|1=Fujiwara no Mototsune}}.

